========================================
26) QUICK INTERVIEW TALKING POINTS
========================================
- PowerShell works with objects, which makes filtering and reporting easier
- I use functions to make scripts modular and reusable
- I use try/catch for reliability and cleaner error handling
- I use PSCustomObject for structured output and reporting
- I use foreach loops when working through server lists
- I use the pipeline heavily for filtering, selecting, and transforming data
- I use Invoke-RestMethod for API calls and automation

========================================
27) VERY COMMON PATTERN
========================================
$results = @()

foreach ($item in $items) {
    try {
        $results += [PSCustomObject]@{
            Name   = $item
            Status = "Success"
            Note   = ""
        }
    }
    catch {
        $results += [PSCustomObject]@{
            Name   = $item
            Status = "Failed"
            Note   = $_.Exception.Message
        }
    }
}

$results

========================================
28) BEST PRACTICES
========================================
- Use clear function names
- Use parameters instead of hardcoding values
- Use try/catch for risky actions
- Return structured objects, not messy text
- Export results to CSV for reports
- Test small pieces before building a large script
- Add comments only where they help
- Keep scripts modular

========================================
29) SIMPLE MENTAL MODEL
========================================
PowerShell flow:
Get data -> Filter it -> Loop through it -> Handle errors -> Output report

Example:
Get-Service |
Where-Object { $_.Status -eq "Running" } |
Select-Object Name, Status

========================================
30) ONE SIMPLE LAB TO PRACTICE
========================================
1. Get all services
2. Filter running services
3. Select name and status
4. Export to CSV

Commands:
$services = Get-Service
$running = $services | Where-Object { $_.Status -eq "Running" }
$report = $running | Select-Object Name, Status
$report | Export-Csv "C:\Temp\running_services.csv" -NoTypeInformation

========================================
31) ANOTHER SIMPLE LAB FOR API
========================================
$response = Invoke-RestMethod -Uri "https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/users"

$response | Select-Object name, email, phone |
Export-Csv "C:\Temp\api_users.csv" -NoTypeInformation

========================================
32) REMEMBER THESE TERMS
========================================
Cmdlet       = built-in PowerShell command
Function     = your reusable code block
Pipeline     = pass output from one command to another
Object       = structured data with properties
Parameter    = input to command/function
PSCustomObject = custom structured output
Try/Catch    = error handling
ScriptBlock  = code inside { }
